Two adult specimens (MHNCUP/REP 193,195, formerly UP-MHNFCP-017410 and 017409 respectively; 
<figureCitation box="[392,491,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURE S" captionStartId="77.[151,248,2012,2036]" captionTargetBox="[177,1410,1116,1986]" captionTargetId="figure-38@77.[177,1410,1116,1986]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="FIGURE S72. Specimen of Dasypeltis cf. scabra (MHNCUP/REP 193), from unknown locality. Photo by Bruna Santos." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5454127" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5454127/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. S72</figureCitation>
), collected from unknown locality, date unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,582,1041]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,654,680]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Comments:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[345,547,655,681]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Dasypeltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis box="[345,547,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Dasypeltis scabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a savanna and grassland species widely distributed in East African savannas and known from all of 
<collectingCountry box="[410,495,691,717]" name="Angola" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Angola</collectingCountry>
, apart from the southwestern desert (
<bibRefCitation author="Bates, M. F. &amp; Broadley, D. G." box="[912,1182,691,717]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="1 - 95" refId="ref33661" refString="Bates, M. F. &amp; Broadley, D. G. (2018) A revision of the egg-eating snakes of the genus Dasypeltis Wagler (Squamata: Colubridae: Colubrinae) in north-eastern Africa and south-western Arabia, with descriptions of three new species. Indago, 34 (1), 1 - 95. https: // doi. org / 10.5281 / zenodo. 1286493" type="journal article" year="2018">Bates &amp; Broadley 2018</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Marques, M. P. &amp; Ceriaco, L. M. P. &amp; Blackburn, D. C. &amp; Bauer, A. M." box="[1194,1425,691,717]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="1 - 501" refId="ref38562" refString="Marques, M. P., Ceriaco, L. M. P., Blackburn, D. C. &amp; Bauer, A. M. (2018) Diversity and distribution of the amphibians and terrestrial reptiles of Angola atlas of historical and bibliographic records (1840 - 2017). Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, Series 4, 65 (Supplement 2), 1 - 501." type="journal article" year="2018">
Marques 
<emphasis box="[1300,1357,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Ferreira, J. B." box="[151,322,727,753]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="111 - 117" refId="ref37152" refString="Ferreira, J. B. (1904) Reptis e amphibios de Angola da regiao ao norte do Quanza (Colleccao Newton 1903). Jornal de Sciencias Mathematicas Physicas e Naturaes, Segunda Serie, 7 (25), 111 - 117." type="journal article" year="1904">Ferreira (1904)</bibRefCitation>
cited several “adult and semi-adult” specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[895,1096,727,753]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Dasypeltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis box="[895,1096,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Dasypeltis scabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with no indication of locality. The author noted that one of the specimens presented an “unusual melanistic coloration” (possibly MHNCUP/REP 195). Later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ferreira, J. B." box="[291,462,799,826]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="159 - 171" refId="ref37198" refString="Ferreira, J. B. (1906) Algumas especies novas ou pouco conhecidas de amphibios e reptis de Angola (Coleccao Newton - 1903 - 1904). Jornal de Sciencias Mathematicas Physicas e Naturaes, Segunda Serie, 7 (26), 159 - 171." type="journal article" year="1906">Ferreira (1906)</bibRefCitation>
published 
<specimenCount box="[587,694,799,825]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="adult">two adult</specimenCount>
specimens, one “dark brown with imperceptible black drawings” (no locality data; likely MHNCUP/REP 193) and another from “Cambondo” as “ 
<taxonomicName box="[1077,1338,835,861]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Dasypeltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="variety" species="scabra" variety="inornata">
<emphasis box="[1077,1189,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">D. scabra</emphasis>
var 
<emphasis box="[1242,1338,835,860]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">inornata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” (junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[297,410,871,897]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Dasypeltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis box="[297,410,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">D. scabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Recently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Bates, M. F. &amp; Broadley, D. G." box="[552,843,871,897]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="1 - 95" refId="ref33661" refString="Bates, M. F. &amp; Broadley, D. G. (2018) A revision of the egg-eating snakes of the genus Dasypeltis Wagler (Squamata: Colubridae: Colubrinae) in north-eastern Africa and south-western Arabia, with descriptions of three new species. Indago, 34 (1), 1 - 95. https: // doi. org / 10.5281 / zenodo. 1286493" type="journal article" year="2018">Bates &amp; Broadley (2018)</bibRefCitation>
reviewed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagler" authorityYear="1830" box="[965,1083,871,897]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Dasypeltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[965,1083,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Dasypeltis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from north-eastern Africa and southwestern Arabia, describing three new species previously considered as part of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1083,1193,907,933]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Dasypeltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis box="[1083,1193,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">D. scabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Branch, W. R." box="[1207,1369,907,933]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="159" refId="ref34681" refString="Branch, W. R. (2018) Snakes of Angola: An annotated checklist. Amphibian &amp; Reptile Conservation, General Section, 12 (2), e 159, 41 - 82." type="journal article" year="2018">Branch (2018)</bibRefCitation>
listed 
<taxonomicName authority="Trape and Mane 2006" authorityName="Trape and Mane" authorityYear="2006" box="[151,545,943,969]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Dasypeltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="confusa">
<emphasis box="[151,276,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">D. confusa</emphasis>
Trapé and Mané 2006
</taxonomicName>
as present in 
<collectingCountry box="[713,798,943,969]" name="Angola" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Angola</collectingCountry>
, following 
<bibRefCitation author="Bates, M. F. &amp; Broadley, D. G." box="[933,1265,943,969]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="1 - 95" refId="ref33661" refString="Bates, M. F. &amp; Broadley, D. G. (2018) A revision of the egg-eating snakes of the genus Dasypeltis Wagler (Squamata: Colubridae: Colubrinae) in north-eastern Africa and south-western Arabia, with descriptions of three new species. Indago, 34 (1), 1 - 95. https: // doi. org / 10.5281 / zenodo. 1286493" type="journal article" year="2018">Bates and Broadley’s (2018)</bibRefCitation>
claim that the species’ distribution extended to 
<collectingCountry box="[523,609,979,1005]" name="Angola" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Angola</collectingCountry>
. Further studies need to be done in order to assess the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1235,1347,979,1005]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Dasypeltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis box="[1235,1347,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">D. scabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species complex and its Angolan populations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
